European debt write-downs are inevitable.
Berkeley — "That was just a Greek crisis," "That was just a crisis involving Greece and Ireland," people used to think. But that is no longer the case, because it is clearly a crisis of the Eurozone.
To deal with it is both easier and more difficult than is usually imagined.
The economics of this crisis is quite simple.
Greece has financial problems.
Ireland's banking sector has problems.
Portugal's private debt market has problems.
Spain has problems in all three of the aforementioned aspects.
Although the details vary, the conclusion is the same: these countries all have to undergo a painful process of spending cuts.
The usual approach to offsetting the side effects of contractionary policies is to combine domestic spending cuts with depreciation of the domestic currency.
Depreciation enhances the competitiveness of exports, which is essentially using foreign demand to make up for domestic demand.
However, these countries are all members of the Eurozone and do not have independent currencies that can be devalued; therefore, they can only resort to internal devaluation as a substitute for external devaluation.
They must cut wages, pensions, and other costs to enhance export competitiveness and thereby expand external demand.
In fact, these crisis-hit countries have shown quite a strong determination to tighten their belts.
However, there is one economic variable that has not changed in response to the adjustment of other variables, and that is the debt of the public and private sectors.
The book value of the government's accumulated debt has not changed, and bank debt—except for some debt owed to junior creditors—has also remained largely unchanged.
It is this simple fact that places the internal devaluation strategy in a self-contradictory position: the more wages and other costs are cut, the heavier the burden of accumulated debt becomes in relative terms.
The heavier the debt burden, the more the government and its protectors (such as banks) must cut public spending and increase taxes in order to manage their debt.
This in turn requires more internal devaluation, further increasing the debt burden, creating a vicious cycle that drags the economy into a slump.
Therefore, to make the internal devaluation strategy effective, it is necessary to find ways to reduce the face value of debt.
Government debt must be restructured.
Bank debts must be converted into equity, and when a bank's liabilities exceed its assets, it should be liquidated.
Mortgage debt must also be written down.
It is understandable that policymakers are unwilling to take this path.
The sanctity of contracts.
The government is concerned about losing credibility in the financial markets.
If creditors are mainly foreign, especially foreign banks, write-downs would only burden other countries.
These concerns are not entirely unfounded, but they should not lead to unreasonable conclusions.
There are only two options: internal depreciation or external depreciation.
The leaders of European countries must choose between the two options.
They unanimously ruled out the possibility of external devaluation.
But internal devaluation necessarily requires debt restructuring.
Denying this is both unreasonable and illogical.
The operation of debt restructuring is simple and clear.
The government can issue a batch of debt instruments with face values discounted at a certain ratio relative to the face values of existing debt.
Bondholders can choose either to hold onto their bonds and redeem them at face value, although they have a later maturity date and a lower interest rate; or to accept discounted bonds with a lower face value than existing bonds, but with an earlier maturity date and a higher interest rate.
This isn't cutting-edge technology; people have done this before.
But to succeed, there are three prerequisites.
First, it is necessary to assure bondholders of the safety of the new bonds.
Someone needs to step forward to guarantee these bonds.
In the 1980s, when Latin American debt restructuring was implemented under the Brady Plan, the U.S. Treasury Department played the role of the "guaranteeing elder brother."
Now, the International Monetary Fund and the German government can take on this responsibility.
Second, all countries must act in unison.
Otherwise, a country's restructuring would raise expectations of other countries, leading to a spillover effect.
Finally, banks that have incurred losses due to debt restructuring must consolidate their balance sheets.
These banks need to undergo real stress tests, rather than the mere formalities conducted earlier this year.
If debt restructuring signals capital inadequacy, a comprehensive conversion of debt into equity must be carried out for the relevant banks' liabilities.
If this is not enough, the government must step in to inject capital into the relevant banks.
This also requires consistent action by all countries.
Once banks' balance sheets are consolidated, it may become possible to restructure mortgage debt, bank debt, and other private sector debts without destabilizing the entire financial system.
Now let's talk about the biggest challenge.
All of this requires resolute leadership.
Germany's leaders must acknowledge that the country's banks have significant risk exposure to the debts of peripheral Eurozone nations, and the situation is critical.
They must convince the backroom bosses and voters that using public funds to guarantee debt restructuring and bank recapitalization is a necessary condition for internal devaluation; since Germany is urging other EU countries to adopt this strategy, it should take on the responsibility of providing guarantees without hesitation.
In short, European leaders, particularly those in Germany, need to state the consequences more seriously — otherwise, they will face great difficulties.
Because that's just the way it is.
